<HEADLINE>
<P>
MORNING REPORT: LEGAL FILE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ALEENE MacMINN, Arts and entertainment reports from The Times, national and 
international news services and the nation's press. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Attorneys for KFI-AM (640) filed an appeal Wednesday contesting U.S. District 
Court Judge Richard A. Gadbois' May 4 ruling enjoining the radio station from 
using the term "talk radio" in conjunction with its call letters pending a 
trial on the matter. KABC-AM (790) filed suit against KFI April 3, alleging 
that the slogan "talk radio" had been its trademark for 17 years. KFI has 
argued that the term is a generic one that describes a programming format and, 
therefore, its use cannot be a trademark infringement. The case will go to 
trial later this year. ALEENE MacMINN 
</P>
</TEXT>
