<HEADLINE>
<P>
SALMON ECONOMICAL WAY TO SATISFY HEARTY APPETITES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Canned salmon is a convenient and economical way to satisfy hungry appetites. 
There are a about five different species of Pacific salmon which vary in color 
and texture, all of which provide a rich source of vitamins and minerals and 
should be enjoyed whenever possible. 
</P>
<P>
Among the species of salmon is Chinook, which is rich in oil with easy-to-flake 
flesh. This type is most commonly used in salads. 
</P>
<P>
Chum has a light color, is coarser in texture and is generally less expensive 
than other types of salmon. It is ideal for casseroles and cooked dishes. 
</P>
<P>
Other varieties include Coho, perfect in almost any recipe, and available in 
red or pink; and Red Sockeye -- with its deep red color and high amount oil, it 
can easily be used for sandwiches, salads, hors d'oeuvre or garnishes. 
</P>
<P>
Try this Quick Salmon Rice Casserole, for a fast and good tasting dish, 
whichever type your choose. 
</P>
<P>
Flake 1 (7 3/4-ounce) can salmon into buttered 1 1/2-quart casserole. Stir in 3 
cups cooked rice, 1 tablespoon lemon juice, 1/4 cup chopped celery, 1/2 
teaspoon dill weed, 3/4 cup shredded medium Cheddar cheese, 1 (10 1/2-ounce) 
can cream of mushroom soup and 1/4 cup milk. Bake at 350 degrees 25 to 30 
minutes. Makes 4 servings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
