</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Chile's President Augusto Pinochet said his lame-duck military government and 
the opposition have agreed on democratic changes in the nation's constitution. 
The accord came after two months of unprecedented negotiations and paved the 
way for a national referendum, probably in August, to approve the amendments. 
Patricio Aylwin, leader of a 17-party opposition coalition, said the reforms 
"open the road for an orderly transition to a fully democratic regime." 
Pinochet, who was defeated in a plebiscite last October, would say only that 
the reforms include changes that will make it easier for the new Congress to 
approve further constitutional alterations. 
