<HEADLINE>
<P>
METRO DIGEST / LOCAL NEWS IN BRIEF: AIDS COALITION CHARGES HARASSMENT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A militant AIDS activist group that staged a boisterous sit-in at a Board of 
Supervisors meeting earlier this month charged Wednesday that its members have 
been harassed by sheriff's deputies. 
</P>
<P>
At a news conference outside the Hall of Administration in Los Angeles, members 
of AIDS Coalition To Unleash Power distributed a chronology of eight incidents 
of alleged harassment they said occurred between May 15 and 25. 
</P>
<P>
"We're being harassed because we're activists and we've protested the Board of 
Supervisors' AIDS policies," said Connie Norman, a member of the group. 
</P>
<P>
The Sheriff's Department did not comment on the allegations. 
</P>
<P>
The alleged incidents included members of the group being stopped in a car by 
deputies and searched for 40 minutes following an ACT-UP meeting in West 
Hollywood, and anonymous telephone calls to employers of ACT-UP members by 
callers asking questions about the employees' involvement with the group. 
</P>
<P>
Fifteen ACT-UP members were arrested May 16 after they disrupted a supervisors 
meeting. 
</P>
